President Uhuru Kenyatta on Saturday joined mourners at the burial of Mzee William Gatuhi Murathe at his farm in Gatanga, Murang&rsquo;a County.Speaking at the funeral service at PCEA Kirwara Church, President Kenyatta eulogised Mzee Murathe, who was a prominent businessman from Murang&rsquo;a, as a hardworking man who played a leading role in community development. &ldquo;Murathe is an excellent example of how to give back to society because he devoted his time and resources to improve the community,&rdquo; Kenyatta said.The late Murathe was the father of Jubilee Partys' Vice-Chairman and former Gatanga MP David Wakairu Murathe. He also praised Murathe&rsquo;s business acumen that saw him excel in all the enterprises he ventured into."Murathe was a pioneer businessman and succeeded through hard work.The history of Murathe and the Rwathia Group, who have done a lot for Kenya, must never be forgotten.,&rdquo;Kenyatta added. Transport Cabinet Secretary James Macharia, who said Murathe&rsquo;s business acumen inspired him in the early days of his career, noted that voter registration in Murang&rsquo;a was massive and urged residents to come out in large numbers to vote on August 8.Kenyatta also took the opportunity to call for peace as political campaigns kick in ahead of the August 8th polls. Cabinet secretaries Eugene Wamalwa (Water and Irrigation), Mwangi Kiunjuri (Devolution) were present during the funeral. Others include MPs Jamleck Kamau (Kigumo), Irungu Kang&rsquo;ata (Kiharu), Moses Kuria (Gatundu South) and Murang&rsquo;a County Assembly Speaker Nduati Kariuki.